John Edward: Language skills needed by the world's citizens
Scottish independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which was continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding test results, and further emphasised by individual and collective achievements in sport, the arts, music and other community activities.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare students for further education and higher education, the careers they want, and to make them citizens of the world.
As the education sector can design and implement the said school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be the preferred and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his native language, it goes to his heart.
This statement is a powerful reminder that we cannot use English alone if we want to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results of this year's final exams show that the highest marks in languages were achieved by pupils from independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who learned foreign languages received excellent grades.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of pupils achieved an excellent score in Mandarin, while 72% of pupils learning German, 69% of pupils learning French and 63% of pupils learning Spanish also achieved the highest possible score.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will surely need in the future.
Today, languages as electives are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools, as elsewhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that 17% of employers are unable to fill jobs due to a lack of a labour force with language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly becoming an imperative for preparing young people for careers.
As more and more jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of their career choice, those who learn a foreign language will in the future experience the benefits of such long-term skills.
A person who speaks more than one language can communicate directly with strangers, and this gives him an advantage over his competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4000 adults, 75% of UK respondents do not know a foreign language well enough to communicate in it, and French is the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of respondents, or 15%.
So investing in language learning is very important for today's children.
If children learn more languages, especially those of developing countries, they will have a better chance of finding good employment.
In Scotland, every school offers a variety of languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their curriculum, while others will choose the languages considered to be the most important in the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child's interests, independent schools will always have a wide range of options, as will teaching staff who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools provide an environment in which children learn to prepare and equip themselves with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It cannot be overlooked that in today's global business world, language skills are so important for the future of any country that they must be reflected in education.
So, knowing modern languages really should be viewed as an "international communication skill".
Independent schools will continue to offer language choice, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
It must be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council
