North Korea has declared that there is no chance of unilateral disarmament without confidence.
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that further sanctions increase mistrust in the United States and that there is no chance that North Korea will unilaterally disarm and give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN General Assembly that North Korea last year took "significant measures of goodwill", such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test station and making a decision to stop developing nuclear technology and weapons.
"However, we have not received a satisfactory response from the United States", he added.
"If we don't trust the United States, we don't trust our national security, and under such circumstances, there's no way we're going to be the first to unilaterally disarm".
While Ri reiterated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "gradual" approach to denuclearization that would gradually lift sanctions on North Korea, his statement is significant because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri was referring to the joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first ever meeting between the current US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea wants to officially end the Korean War, which lasted from 1950 to 1953, but the U.S. has demanded that Pyongyang give up its nuclear weapons before that.
Washington has also ignored calls for easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
The US insists on denuclearization first and increases pressure through sanctions to forcefully achieve its goal, even opposing the declaration of an end to the war, Ri added.
The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is just a delusion of people who know nothing about us.
The main problem is that continuing sanctions increase mistrust.
Ri did not mention whether there were plans for a second Kim-Trump meeting that the US president had talked about earlier this week at the United Nations.
But the minister pointed out that Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in had held as many as three meetings in the last five months, adding: "If denuclearization had been sought by South Korea, not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to this halt".
Regardless, the tone of Minister Ri's speech was vastly different from last year when he spoke before the UN General Assembly and declared that the targeting of the continental United States with missiles was inevitable after the evil President Trump called Kim a "human rocket" on a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened "total destruction" of North Korea, this year at the United Nations praised Kim for his courage to disarm, but added that they still had a lot of work to do and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea denuclearizes.
