Students at Harvard are taking a course on how to get a good rest
A new course at Harvard University has enabled all students to get a good night's sleep in an attempt to combat the increasingly pervasive culture of caffeinated learning and sleepless nights.
The academic found that students at the world's top university often have no idea about the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep science at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has devised a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl came up to me and said, "Why did I only learn this now, in my last year of college?"
She said no one had told her how important sleep was, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being offered for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help academic and athletic achievement and improve overall health.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health service, says that the university decided to introduce the course after students were observed to have a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course consists of a series of interactive tasks.
One of these tasks involved a picture of a student's dorm room where students had to click on cups of coffee, curtains, tennis shoes, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how lack of sleep affects performance, and the importance of a sleep routine.
During the lecture, students also learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Then a campus map is displayed with interactive icons that encourage students to reflect on their daily routine.
We know that student behavior won't change immediately.
But we feel that they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect your health", added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of studying all night before exams is still alive, says the professor, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure on students prove that lack of sleep is a growing problem.
The professor says that the secret weapon of students against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety should be good, quality sleep, which also helps fight obesity because lack of sleep affects the brain, putting it into a state of starvation and causing constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending his first year at Harvard.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to expand the course to the entire campus.
As a next step, it plans to ask all postgraduates to complete a similar course of study before joining a competing institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students turn on their alarm during sleep as well as when they wake up, being aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic devices, as well as LED lights that can disrupt their circadian rhythms and cause sleep problems.
